-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Mauritius Commercial, Omnicane, Sameer Africa
-- B y   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r
-- 2010-11-15T16:42:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-15/sub-saharan-african-stocks-mauritius-commercial-omnicane-sameer-africa.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  climbed for
a second day, adding 0.3 percent to close at 84.42 by 3 p.m. in
Nairobi, the highest in a week.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  added 0.5 percent to close at
1,898.37 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. The  Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated for a second day,
slipping 0.3 percent to 25,301.34 by the 1 p.m. in Lagos,
according to data from the bourse’s website, while Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  snapped two days of gains, falling
0.2 percent to 859.63 by the close at 5 p.m. in Windhoek. The
 Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  surged 1.7 percent, to
6,921.36 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra, the highest since Oct. 1.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mauritius Commercial Bank Ltd.  (MCB MP), the nation’s
biggest lender by market value, rose for the first time in four
days, adding 2 rupees, or 1.3 percent, to 152 rupees. Axys
Stockbroking Ltd. estimates the lender’s profit for the year
through June 2011 will advance 12 percent to 3.83 billion rupees
($127 million), the Port Louis-based brokerage said in an e-
mailed note to clients today.  Omnicane Ltd.  (MTMD MP), a Mauritian sugar producer,
rallied 2.5 rupees, or 3.7 percent, to 70.5 rupees, the highest
in a month. The company reported net income of 89 million rupees
in the third quarter through September from a loss of 21 million
rupees a year earlier, the Port Louis-based company said in an
e-mailed statement to the Stock Exchange of Mauritius today.  Sameer Africa Ltd.  (SAME KN), a Kenyan tire manufacturer,
dropped the most since Sept. 1, retreating 30 cents, or 3.8
percent, to 7.65 rupees. The company expects earnings for the
year through December to be “lower than current market
expectations,” it said in a statement e-mailed by the Nairobi
Stock Exchange after the market closed on Nov. 12.  To contact the reporter on this story:
